“…because of that” can lead in a few different directions, depending on what you mean.

One interpretation is:

We’re all improvising more than we’d like to admit.

Most people don’t have a complete manual for life. They learn roles, make decisions with incomplete information, adapt after mistakes, and gradually become more competent. In that sense, many adults are “figuring it out as they go.”

If that’s what you mean, then an interesting consequence is:

* Confidence isn’t the same as certainty.
* Expertise often includes knowing what you don’t know.
* Social roles are partially performances, but they can still become authentic through practice.

Someone may start by “acting like a leader,” and over years of experience, actually become one.

Another consequence is empathy. If everyone is improvising to some extent, it’s easier to meet people with curiosity rather than assuming they have everything under control.

The phrase “fake it till you make it” captures a slice of this, but I’d phrase it more carefully:

We often grow into the roles we initially practice.

The performance and the person don’t have to remain separate forever. Sometimes the role shapes the individual just as the individual shapes the role.

I’m curious what your “…because of that” was going to be. That’s where I suspect your point differs from the common saying.